    "summary": "Avebury is a Neolithic henge monument in Wiltshire, England, comprising one of the largest stone circles in the world. Construction began around 3000 BCE, with the great outer circle enclosing a ditch and bank roughly 430 meters in diameter. The complex includes two smaller inner stone circles and was connected by ceremonial avenues of standing stones to neighboring monuments.\n\nThe scale of the undertaking required the organized labor of many hundreds of people over generations, reflecting the complex social structures of late Neolithic Britain. The purpose of the monument remains debated, but it was likely a center of ritual, assembly, and ancestor veneration. Avebury forms part of a broader prehistoric landscape that includes nearby passage tombs such as West Kennet Long Barrow and the great mound of Silbury Hill, illustrating the dense concentration of Neolithic monumental construction across the Wiltshire landscape.",
